n Catholic]]\n|signature    =\n|website      = http://rokita.house.gov/\n|footnotes    =\n}}\n\n'''Theodore Edward \"Todd\" Rokita''' (born February 9, 1970) is an [[United States|American]] politician who has been a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from {{ushr|IN|4}} since 2011. Rokita, a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], previously served two terms as [[Secretary of State of Indiana]] from 2002 to 2010. When Rokita was elected to office in 2002 at the age of 32, he became at the time the youngest [[Secretary of State (U.S. state government)|secretary of state]] in the [[United States]].\n\n==Early life, education and career==\nRokita grew up in [[Munster, Indiana|Munster]], located in [[Lake County, Indiana|Lake County]] in [[Northwest Indiana]]. Rokita attended [[Munster High School]].<ref name=\"Franklin\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nwitimes.com/news/local/lake/munster/munster-speech-team-takes-top-state-honors-for-lucky-th/article_f446a3fe-f6ab-5890-8d6d-6f7cf23c53eb.html | title=Munster speech team takes top state honors for lucky 13th time | date=17 May 2012 | accessdate=17 January 2014 | author=Franklin, Lu Ann}}</ref> He holds a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from [[Wabash College]] in [[Crawfordsville, Indiana]], where he was an [[Eli Lilly and Company|Eli Lilly]] Fellow. He is a member of the [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity.<ref>http://weblinks.sigmachi.org/preview/marketing/PAC/list.pdf</ref> He has a law degree from [[Indiana University Robert H. McKinney School of Law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=R000592 |title=ROKITA, Todd - Biographical Information |publisher=Bioguide.congress.gov |date= |accessdate=2013-10-21}}</ref>\n\nRokita was a practicing attorney. In 1997 he joined the secretary of state's office as general counsel. He later became deputy secretary of state.<ref name=\"vote-in.org\">{{cite web|url=http://vote-in.org/Intro.aspx?State=IN&Id=INRokitaTodd |title=Vote In biographical profile of Todd Rokita |publisher=Vote-in.org |date= |accessdate=2013-10-21}}</ref>\n\n==Indiana Secretary of State==\nRokita was elected by his peers nationally to serve on the nine-member federal executive board of the Election Assistance Commission.<ref name=\"vote-in.org\" /> The commission is charged by law to address election reform issues on a nation-wide basis. Rokita has testified about Indiana's voting reform efforts before the United States Congress.\n\nRokita was a named defendant in the Hoosier State's voter identification case went before the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] on January 9, 2008; the combined cases of ''[[Crawford v. Marion County Election Board]]'' (07-21) and ''[[Indiana Democratic Party v. Rokita]]'' (07-25) involved the Indiana voting requirement laws that require voters display state-issued photo IDs before voting. In April 2008, the US Supreme Court upheld that law. Rokita also served as Indiana's chief [[securities fraud]] investigator.\n\nAs secretary of state, Rokita visited each of Indiana's ninety-two counties at least once per year. Rokita was named as one of the \"40 under 40\" by the ''Indianapolis Business Journal''.{{When|date=April 2011}} Rokita was active in the [[National Association of Secretaries of State]] (NASS), and after serving as the elected treasurer, he became the President for the 2007-2008 term.<ref>{{cite web|author=InsideINdianaBusiness.com Report |url=http://www.insideindianabusiness.com/newsitem.asp?ID=24474 |title=Rokita Becomes President of National Association of Secretaries of State - Newsroom - Inside INdiana Business with Gerry Dick |publisher=Insideindianabusiness.com |date=2007-07-18 |accessdate=2010-08-23}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2009, Rokita outlined a plan to reform how Indiana's legislative districts are drawn to reduce [[gerrymandering]]. He proposed making it a felony for lawmakers to use political data or incumbents' addresses when drawing electoral maps. [[Indiana's congressional districts]] and districts for the [[Indiana Senate]] and [[Indiana House of Representatives]] will next be redrawn after the [[2010 United States Census|2010 Census]]. Rokita says boundaries should follow existing county and township lines, and that each of the 50 senate districts should be divided into two house districts, claiming this will lead to more competitive legislative elections.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.indystar.com/article/20090908/NEWS05/909080333/Lawmakers+draw+line+at+redistricting+plan|title=Lawmakers draw a line at Rokita's redistricting plan|last=Schneider|first=Mary Beth |date=September 8, 2009|work=The Indianapolis Star|accessdate=2009-09-08}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education|Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education]] (Chairman)\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Workforce Protections|Subcommittee on Workforce Protections]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on House Administration|Committee on House Administration]]'''\n\n==Controversies==\nOn Aug. 4th 2014, on an Indianapolis radio program, while discussing the [[2014 American immigration crisis]] Rokita expressed concerns about the ability of border patrol agents to properly process and screen individuals entering the country illegally.  He stated that \u201cfrom a public-health standpoint\u201d that we \u201cneed to know the condition of these kids\u201d while citing the [[Ebola virus epidemic in West Africa]] as a news event that shows how rapidly diseases can spread.  In response to reports stating that Rokita believed that illegal immigrants are carrying Ebola, he clarified that \u201cthe sudden spread of Ebola in Africa is merely one example of how we must take deliberate care to prevent an outbreak of any type of disease inside our borders.\u201d<ref>http://rokita.house.gov/press-release/rokita-response-column-border-crisis</ref> Rokita also cited news reports indicating that nationals from 75 different countries had been apprehended between 2010 and 2014 illegally crossing the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]].<ref>https://soundcloud.com/93wibc/garrison8-4-final</ref>\n\nIn October 2013 during the American government shutdown, Rokita was interviewed by CNN journalist Carol Costello. Her pointed questions about Rokita's defense of the shutdown that furloughed hundreds of thousands of government employees without compensation while he continued to receive his paycheck, were eventually countered with his statement that she was \"beautiful but you have to be honest\" and that journalists were part of the problem.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fung|first=Katherine|title=Rep. Todd Rokita To CNN's Carol Costello: 'You're Beautiful But You Have To Be Honest'|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/03/todd-rokita-carol-costello-cnn-beautiful_n_4036782.html|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=25 October 2013|date=October 3, 2013}}</ref> The Congressman's office issued a statement that he intended no offense by his comments.\n\nIn April 2007, Rokita was speaking at a Republican event, and encouraged Republicans to reach out to African-Americans. He mentioned 90 percent of [[African Americans]] vote [[U.S. Democratic Party|Democratic]], after which he asked, \"How can that be? Ninety to ten. Who's the master and who's the slave in that relationship? How can that be healthy?\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.idsnews.com/news/NewStoryPrint.aspx?id=54177 | title =Racist remark angers lawmakers Representative: Secretary of State should apologize | author =Alexandra R. Moses, Mike Smith  | author2 =''[[Associated Press]]'' | publisher =''[[Indiana Daily Student]]''}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/politics/todd-rokita-r--20101024 | title =Todd Rokita (R) | author =Brendan Sasso | publisher =nationaljournal.com | date =November 3, 2010}}</ref>  Four days after making those remarks, he apologized.<ref>[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2007/04/16/national/a124340D15.DTL&type=politics \"Ind. Exec Apologizes for Slavery Remark\"], ''Associated Press'', April 16, 2007</ref> Rokita also met privately with eleven members of the Indiana Black Legislative Caucus to apologize for the comment. Representative [[Vernon Smith (Indiana politician)|Vernon Smith]], D-[[Gary, Indiana|Gary]], told reporters, \u201cHe apologized to our satisfaction. We do believe he was sincere in his apology,\" Smith said. \"I think there are greater issues &mdash; education, health, economics for the black community &mdash; that are more important than us spending all this time on a slip of the lip. I do believe that we all make mistakes (and) that if we expect to be forgiven, we need to forgive.\" During the course of the same private meeting Rokita was told his office should reflect the diversity of the state, at the time of his remarks 89% of the employees in Rokita's office were white. <ref>[http://www.theindychannel.com/news/politics/rokita-apologizes-to-black-lawmakers-for-slave-remark], WRTV-6, April 18, 2007</ref>\n\n==Political campaigns==\n===2010===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Indiana, 2010#District 4}}\nOn February 1, 2010, three days after Congressman [[Steve Buyer]] of {{ushr|Indiana|4}} said that he would retire at the end of his term, Rokita posted an announcement on [[Facebook]] making clear his intentions to run for the open seat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jconline.com/article/20100202/ELECTION01/2020334|title=Hershman, Rokita among growing field for Buyer's seat|date=February 2, 2010|accessdate=February 2, 2010|work=[[Journal & Courier]]|first=Mary Beth|last=Schneider}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nBuyer's announcement touched off a free-for-all among area Republicans to succeed him.  Ultimately,  thirteen candidates entered the Republican primary, including Rokita.  With a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of R+14, the 4th is one of the most Republican districts in the [[Eastern Time Zone]] and tied for the second-most Republican in the state (behind the 5th District).  It was taken for granted that whoever won the primary would be heavily favored to be the district's next congressman.\n\nRokita won the primary with 42 percent of the vote, and went on to win the general election with 68.6% of the vote.\n\n==Tenure==\n;Agriculture\nRokita is against federal government regulation over farming. A representative of a heavy-farming district in [[Indiana]], Rokita has voted in favor of deregulating farmer restrictions, earning him an \"A\" rating from the American Farm Bureau Federation.<ref>[http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/34167/todd-rokita/4] \"American Farm Bureau Federation interest group ranking\"</ref> He co-sponsored the Farm Dust Regulation Prevention Act- passing the house in March 2011- in order to prevent the \"significant burden on small businesses for little obvious environmental benefit.\" Rokita also co-sponsored the Preserving America's Family Farms Act- which passed the House in July 2012- citing Indiana's dependence on youth work on family farms.<ref name=\"toddrokitaforcongress1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.toddrokitaforcongress.com/about.html |title=Todd Rokita for Congress |publisher=Todd Rokita for Congress |date= |accessdate=2013-10-21}}</ref>\n\n;Health Care\nRokita opposes any Health Care regulation that increases the national debt, earning a \"B\" rating by the National Taxpayers Union 2011 Positions on Tax and Spending.<ref>[http://votesmart.org/interest-group/872/rating/5941] \"National Taxpayers Union interest group rating\" </ref> He opposes the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] and was the key vote to repeal the health care law and health care-related provisions in the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010.<ref>[http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c112:hr2:] \"bill text\"</ref> His healthcare voting record has given him an extremely low approval ratings from care-related interest groups such as the Association of University Centers on Disabilities and the American Nurses Association.<ref>[http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/34167/todd-rokita/38] \"Health care interest group ratings\" </ref>\n\n;Gun Control\nRokita is a strong supporter of the [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|Second Amendment]], saying \"I\u2019m proud of my 'A' rating from the [[National Rifle Association|NRA]]. If we are going to keep up our traditions and pass them on to our children, we need leaders in Congress who understand, and will fight every day, to protect our 2nd Amendment right to keep and bear arms.\"<ref name=\"toddrokitaforcongress1\"/><ref>[http://votesmart.org/candidate/evaluations/34167/todd-rokita/37]\"[[National Rifle Association|NRA]] interest group rating\"</ref> Rokita voted in favor of a bill \"Requiring State Reciprocity for Carrying Concealed Firearms\" in November 2011.<ref>[http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/34167/todd-rokita/37/gun-issues]\"Gun issues voting record\" </ref>\n\n;Taxes\nIn 2010 Rokita signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any Global Warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>http://americansforprosperity.org/files/Rokita_Todd.pdf</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nOn April 2, 2014, Rokita introduced the [[Strengthening Education through Research Act (H.R. 4366; 113th Congress)]].<ref name=4366allactions>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4366 - All Actions|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4366/all-actions/|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=6 May 2014}}</ref> The bill would amend and [[authorization bill|reauthorize]] the [[Education Sciences Reform Act of 2002]] and would authorize the [[appropriations bill (United States)|appropriation]] of $615 million for fiscal year 2015 and $3.8 billion over the 2015-2019 period to support federal educational research, statistical analysis, and other activities.<ref name=cbo4366>{{cite web|title=CBO - H.R. 4366|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45300|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=6 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nRokita is a member of the Director's Circle of the Indiana Council for Economic Education, the state bar association, the Knights of Columbus, and the National Rifle Association. A commercial-rated pilot, Rokita volunteers his time by flying people in need of non-emergency medical care to hospitals and clinics throughout the Midwest for treatment and is a member of the Indiana chapter of the International Flying Farmers. Rokita has also served as Chair of NASS's New Millennium Young Voters Summit of 2004, chair of the standing Voter Participation Committee and vice chair of the Securities Regulation Committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rokita.house.gov/about-me/full-biography |title=Full Biography &#124; Congressman Todd Rokita |publisher=Rokita.house.gov |date=2012-01-27 |accessdate=2013-10-21}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://rokita.house.gov/ Congressman Todd Rokita] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.toddrokita.com Todd Rokita for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Indiana/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Todd_Rokita_%5BR-4%5D}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = R000592 | ballot = Todd_Rokita | nndb = 903/000266105 | votesmart = 34167 | govtrack = 412426 | opencong = 412426 | rollcall = 31051 | politifact = | fec = H0IN04170 | opensecrets = N00031741 | assets = todd-rokita | legistorm = 2753/Rep_Todd_Rokita_IN.html | followthemoney = 18679 | ontheissues = IN/Todd_Ro